    "substrate_derivation_note": "endpoint_distance_substrate_image E(coord) := log2(|base_operand(coord)|) where base_operand is the radicand 1 - psi(t) of the natural function sqrt(base_operand) for each fixture. Derivation chain from IEEE 754 substrate (sketch; not a formal proof): (i) BACL [proven in bacl_invariant_audit/closeout.md] gives 1 - x_term = j * ulp(x_term) for integer j when ulp(1) >= ulp(x_term); (ii) the lattice unit is ulp(x_term) = 2^(k_x_term - 52) where k_x_term = floor(log2(|x_term|)); (iii) the result base_operand = 1 - x_term then sits in a binade k_b = floor(log2(|base_operand|)), so its float64 intrinsic granularity is 2^(k_b - 52); (iv) the ratio between the BACL lattice unit (~ ulp(x_term)) and the result's intrinsic granularity (~ ulp(base_operand)) governs how the route-pair rounding decisions distribute against the lattice \u2014 and that ratio depends on k_b = floor(E). Empirical observation across P1+P2+P2b+P2c: F1_to_F2 half_phase fraction varies with E systematically. This pass tests four relation families (continuous monotone, threshold, residual, transition grammar) against E and produces an honest characterization. Formal derivation of the ratio-to-phase mapping is a separate deliverable beyond Phase 2d."
